text:
Swisscom AG is Switzerland’s leading telecommunications and information technology company. It is headquartered in Ittigen, near Bern, and has a significant presence in Italy through its subsidiary Fastweb. Swisscom offers a comprehensive range of services, including mobile and fixed-line telephony, broadband internet, digital television, and various IT services. As of 2023, the company employs approximately 19,729 full-time equivalents and reported revenues exceeding 11 billion CHF.

Swisscom has a rich history, tracing its origins back to 1851 with the establishment of a state-run telegraph service in Switzerland. The company evolved over the years, becoming part of the PTT (Post, Telegraph, and Telephone) in 1920. In 1997, the telecommunications division was split from postal services to form Swisscom, which was partially privatized in 1998.

Swisscom is organized into several key segments: Swisscom Switzerland, which serves customers within Switzerland; Fastweb, which operates in Italy and offers broadband internet, digital television, and mobile services; and other subsidiaries and brands, such as Wingo, Coop Mobile, and M-Budget Mobile.

In Switzerland, Swisscom dominates the telecommunications sector with significant market shares in mobile communications (56%), broadband internet (51%), and digital television (37%). In Italy, Fastweb holds a substantial market share with 16% among private broadband customers and 29% among corporate clients.

Financially, Swisscom has demonstrated consistent performance, with 2023 revenues reported at 11.072 billion CHF, an EBITDA of 4.406 billion CHF, and a net profit of 1.603 billion CHF. The company is also recognized for innovation and sustainability, investing in research and development and implementing initiatives to reduce environmental impact.

Recent developments include Swisscom’s announcement in March 2024 of plans to merge its Italian subsidiary Fastweb with Vodafone Italia, aiming to bolster its position in the Italian market.

Swisscom operates in a competitive landscape in Switzerland, facing challenges from companies like Sunrise and UPC, but it remains a leader in various market segments. The company is also known for its technological advancements, such as launching its 5G network in 2019.
